In the United States, a '''speaking indictment''' is an [[indictment]] that goes beyond the mere statement of charges, thus putting statements about alleged events into the public domain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/what-speaking-indictment-muellers-key-tool-russia-investigation-1089564|title=Robert Mueller appears to be using an obscure tool in his Russia investigation|date=2018-08-24|work=Newsweek|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, it was reported that speaking indictments had been used as part of the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017–present)|Mueller Inquiry]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference with the American political process]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/402902-muellers-speaking-indictments-offer-clues-to-strategy|title=Mueller's 'speaking indictments' offer clues to strategy|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=2018-08-24|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/russia-indictments-lay-the-foundation-for-broader-conspiracy-charges-says-former-fbi-special-counsel|title=Russia indictments lay the foundation for broader conspiracy charges, says former FBI special counsel|last=|first=|date=Feb 19, 2018|website=PBS NewsHour|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>

