A '''white backlash''' is an actual or hypothetical negative response of [[white people]] to racial progress. It is typically discussed in [[the United States]] in regard to advancement of [[African American]]s in American society,<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hughey |first=Matthew W. |date=2014-03-18 |title=White backlash in the ‘post-racial’ United States |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01419870.2014.886710 |journal=Ethnic and Racial Studies |volume=37 |issue=5 |pages=721–730 |doi=10.1080/01419870.2014.886710}}</ref> though it has been discussed in the context of other countries, including the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rhodes |first=James |date=2010-02-09 |title=White Backlash, ‘Unfairness’ and Justifications of British National Party (BNP) Support |url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/1468796809353392 |journal=Ethnicities |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=77–99 |doi=10.1177/1468796809353392}}</ref>

==History in the United States==
One early example of a white backlash occurred when [[Hiram Rhodes Revels]] was elected to the [[United States Senate]] in 1870, becoming the first African-American to be so elected. The resulting backlash derailed the then-ongoing post-Civil War [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]], which had attempted to build an interracial democracy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/11/11/us/obama-trump-white-backlash/index.html |title=This is what 'whitelash' looks like |last=CNN |first=John Blake, |date=2016-11-11 |website=CNN |access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref>

Among the earliest high-profile examples of a white backlash in the United States was in 1964, after the passage of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]]. Many Democrats in Congress, as well as President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] himself, feared that such a backlash could develop in response to the legislation, and [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] popularized the "white backlash" phrase and concept to warn of this possibility.<ref name=atlantic>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/01/trump-massive-resistance-history-mlk/550544/ |title=Five Decades of White Backlash |last=II |first=Vann R. Newkirk |date=2018-01-15 |website=The Atlantic |language=en-US |access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref> The backlash that they warned about did ensue, and was based on the argument that whites' immigrant descendants did not receive the benefits that were given to African Americans in the Civil Rights Act.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/08/23/analysis-of-the-white-backlash.html |title=Analysis of the ‘White Backlash’ |last=Miller |first=William Lee |date=1964-08-23 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2018-02-16 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> After signing the Civil Rights Act, Johnson grew concerned that the white backlash would cost him the [[United States presidential election, 1964|1964 general election]] later that year. Specifically, Johnson feared that his opponent, [[Barry Goldwater]], would harness the backlash by highlighting the black riots engulfing the country at the time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.archives.gov/publications/prologue/2001/spring/lbj-and-white-backlash-1.html |title=LBJ Fights the White Backlash |date=Spring 2001 |website=Prologue Magazine|language=en |access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref>

A significant white backlash also resulted from the election of [[Barack Obama]] as the first black [[President of the United States]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Smith |first=Terry|date=2015 |title=White Backlash in a Brown Country |url=https://scholar.valpo.edu/vulr/vol50/iss1/4/ |journal=Valparaiso University Law Review |language=en |volume=50 |issue=1}}</ref> As a result, the term is often used to refer specifically to the backlash triggered by Obama's election.<ref name=atlantic/> The election of [[Donald Trump]] as president in 2016 is often cited by critics as another example of white backlash.<ref name=atlantic/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/01/08/us/trump-affirmative-action-president/index.html |title=How Trump became 'the white affirmative action president' |last=CNN |first=Story by John Blake, CNN Video by Tawanda Scott Sambou, |date=2018-01-08 |website=CNN |access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref> For example, [[CNN]] contributor [[Van Jones]] coined the term "whitelash" (a [[portmanteau]] of "white" and "backlash") to describe one of the reasons he thought that Trump won the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 election]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/11/11/us/obama-trump-white-backlash/index.html |title=This is what 'whitelash' looks like |last=CNN |first=John Blake, |date=2016-11-11 |work=CNN |access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref>

